John Arrowwood wrote:

&gt;&gt;From: Colin Green &lt;cgreen@...&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;John Arrowwood wrote:
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;What I need is a fitness function that penalizes for this.
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;I have an idea though, perhaps you could try a non-linear error function:
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;How about:
&gt;&gt; error = abs(o-e) ^ 0.3
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Raise it to the power of 0.3?  Hmmm....  I like it!  The fitness must be 10 
&gt;times more accurate in order to get an error report of half as much.
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
Yeh, you reward very close results more than before and then the reward 
drops of quickly.

&gt;&gt;The error rises faster than the difference and maxes out when the
&gt;&gt;difference reaches 1.  An difference at or beyond 1 gets the maximum
&gt;&gt;possible error.
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;So I take it you would cap the error at 1?  Any particular reason?  Just 
&gt;predictability?
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
The maxing out is actually the most significant factor. You could 
actually just use the direct mapping between difference and error that 
you were using, scale it a bit and cap it. e.g.

 error = min(1.0, abs(o-e)*3)

This maxing out means that you only reward for nearby results, anything 
more than 0.33 out will get no reward, therefore an output of zero will 
not get a good fitness score most of the time. I&#39;m not sure if the 
curvature of  x^0.3  is as significant.

&gt;Thanks!  Appreciate the suggestion...cross your fingers! :)
&gt;  
&gt;
No worries. Good luck,

Colin.
